## Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Chat Template Handler

### Context
The Mistral Instruct v0.3 format (`mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3`) currently has no named entry in the lookup table, and its Jinja template string would fall through to the Llama-2 fallback in auto-detection — both incorrect. The plan adds everything in **4 purely additive steps** touching exactly 2 files.

---

### Files to change
| File | Nature of change |
|---|---|
| `src/llama-chat.h` | Append one enum value before `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_UNKNOWN` |
| `src/llama-chat.cpp` | Add map entry, one detection branch, one handler block |

---

### Step 1 — `src/llama-chat.h`: new enum value
Insert immediately before `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_UNKNOWN` (line 61):
```cpp
LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3,
```

### Step 2 — `src/llama-chat.cpp`: named-template map entry
After the `"mistral-v7-tekken"` line (line 38):
```cpp
{ "mistral-instruct-v3", LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3 },
```

### Step 3 — `src/llama-chat.cpp`: auto-detection branch
In `llm_chat_detect_template`, **between** the existing v1/v3 `else if` and the Llama-2 `else` (around line 121), add:
```cpp
} else if (tmpl_contains("'[INST] ' + message['content']")) {
    return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3;
}
```
The pattern `'[INST] ' + message['content']` appears verbatim in the actual Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3 Jinja template. It is absent from v1 (`' [INST] ' + system_message`), v3/v3-tekken (`[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]`), v7 (`[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`), and Llama-2 (`<<SYS>>`), so no existing detection path is affected.

### Step 4 — `src/llama-chat.cpp`: handler implementation
After the MISTRAL_V1/V3/V3_TEKKEN handler closes (~line 291), before the LLAMA_2 handler:
```cpp
} else if (tmpl == LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3) {
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3: system prepended inside first [INST] block
    std::string sys_prompt;
    for (auto message : chat) {
        std::string role(message->role);
        std::string content(message->content);
        if (role == "system") {
            sys_prompt = content;
        } else if (role == "user") {
            ss << "[INST] ";
            if (!sys_prompt.empty()) {
                ss << sys_prompt << "\n\n";
                sys_prompt.clear();
            }
            ss << content << " [/INST]";
        } else {
            ss << content << "</s>";
        }
    }
    if (add_ass) {
        ss << "[INST] ";
    }
```

### Expected output (sys + user + asst + user, add_ass=true)
```
[INST] You are a helpful assistant\n\nHello [/INST]Hi there</s>[INST] Who are you [/INST][INST] 
```

### Verification
1. `--chat-template mistral-instruct-v3` resolves without `std::out_of_range`
2. `llm_chat_detect_template(actual_v0.3_jinja_string)` returns `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3`
3. Handler output matches format spec (system inside first `[INST]`, `</s>` after assistant, no trimming)
4. Full `tests/test-chat-template` suite still passes (no regressions on mistral-v3, mistral-v7, llama2)
5. Template strings containing `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` still route to `MISTRAL_V7`
